The '''Boeing''' (formerly '''McDonnell Douglas''') '''C-17 Globemaster III''' is a large [[military transport aircraft]]. Developed for the [[United States Air Force]] from the 1980s to the early 1990s by [[McDonnell Douglas]], the C-17 is used for rapid [[airlift|strategic airlift]] of troops and [[cargo]] to [[Main Operating Base|main operating bases]] or [[forward operating base]]s throughout the world; it can also perform tactical airlift, [[medical evacuation]] and [[airdrop]] missions.&lt;ref name=AF_fact&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.af.mil/information/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=86 |title = C-17 fact sheet |publisher = US Air Force |date = 22 October 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; The C-17 carries the name of two previous, unrelated U.S. military cargo aircraft, the [[Douglas C-74 Globemaster]] and the [[Douglas C-124 Globemaster II]].

The C-17 is operated by the U.S. Air Force, the [[Royal Air Force|United Kingdom]], [[Royal Australian Air Force|Australia]], [[Canadian Forces Air Command|Canada]],&lt;ref name=&quot;CF_C-17&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.boeing.com/defense-space/military/c17/news/2007/q3/070808c_nr.html |title = Boeing Delivers Canada's First C-17 |publisher = Boeing |date = 8 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[NATO]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&amp;item=764 |title = Multinational Alliance's 1st Boeing C-17 Joins Heavy Airlift Wing in Hungary |publisher = Boeing |date =  27 July 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; and [[Qatar]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Boe_Qatar_1st&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&amp;item=787 |title = Boeing Delivers Qatar's 1st C-17 Globemaster III |publisher = Boeing |date = 11 August 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[United Arab Emirates]] has aircraft on order, and [[India]] has a preliminary agreement to order the aircraft.

==Development==
===Background===
In the 1970s, the U.S. Air Force began looking for a replacement for the [[C-130 Hercules]] tactical airlifter.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/access/72923084.html?dids=72923084:72923084&amp;FMT=ABS&amp;FMTS=ABS:AI&amp;type=historic&amp;date=Nov+13%2C+1972&amp;author=&amp;pub=Wall+Street+Journal&amp;desc=Air+Force+Lets+Advanced+STOL+Prototype+Work&amp;pqatl=google |title = Air Force Lets Advanced STOL Prototype Work |publisher = Wall Street Journal |date = 13 November 1972}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Advanced Medium STOL Transport]] (AMST) competition was held, with [[Boeing Integrated Defense Systems|Boeing]] proposing the [[Boeing YC-14|YC-14]], and [[McDonnell Douglas]] proposing the [[McDonnell Douglas YC-15|YC-15]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/660687842.html?dids=660687842:660687842&amp;FMT=ABS&amp;FMTS=ABS:AI&amp;type=historic&amp;date=Nov+11%2C+1972&amp;author=&amp;pub=Los+Angeles+Times&amp;desc=McDonnell%2C+Boeing+to+Compete+for+Lockheed+C-130+Successor&amp;pqatl=google |title = McDonnell, Boeing to Compete for Lockheed C-130 Successor |publisher = Los Angeles Times |first = Marvin |last = Miles |date = 11 November 1972}}&lt;/ref&gt; Though both entrants exceeded specified requirements, the AMST competition was canceled before a winner had been selected. The Air Force started the C-X program in November 1979 to develop a larger AMST with longer range to augment its strategic airlift.&lt;ref name=&quot;kennedy_part1&quot;&gt;Kennedy 2004, pp. 3-20, 24.&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Yc15-1 072.jpg|thumb|left|The [[McDonnell Douglas]] [[McDonnell Douglas YC-15|YC-15]] design was used as the basis for the C-17.|alt=Top view of cargo aircraft in-flight, trialed by a fighter chase plane. Under each wing are two engines suspended forward ahead the leading edge. ]]

By 1980, the USAF found itself with a large fleet of aging [[C-141 Starlifter]] cargo aircraft. Compounding matters, USAF historically never possessed sufficient strategic airlift capabilities to fulfill its airlift requirements. The USAF set mission requirements and released a request for proposals (RFP) for C-X in October 1980. McDonnell Douglas elected to develop a new aircraft based on the YC-15; Boeing bid an enlarged three-engine version of its AMST YC-14. Lockheed submitted two designs, a C-5-based design and an enlarged C-141 design. On 28 August 1981, McDonnell Douglas was chosen to build its proposed aircraft, by then designated ''C-17''. The new aircraft differed in having swept wings, increased size, and more powerful engines.&lt;ref name=&quot;norton p12-3&quot;&gt;Norton 2001, pp. 12–13.&lt;/ref&gt; This would allow it to perform all work performed by the C-141, but to also fulfill some of the duties of the [[C-5 Galaxy]], freeing the C-5 fleet for outsize cargo.&lt;ref name=&quot;norton p12-3&quot;/&gt;

===Design phase===

Development continued until December 1985, when a full-scale production contract was signed for 210 aircraft.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/673929272.html?dids=673929272:673929272&amp;FMT=ABS&amp;FMTS=ABS:AI&amp;type=historic&amp;date=Jul+02%2C+1984&amp;author=&amp;pub=Los+Angeles+Times&amp;desc=Obstacles+Remain%2C+but+McDonnell+Optimistic+About+Its+C-17+Project&amp;pqatl=google |title = Obstacles Remain, but McDonnell Optimistic About Its C-17 Project |first = Ralph |last = Vartabedian |publisher = Los Angeles Times |date = 2 July 1984}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/98482212.html?dids=98482212:98482212&amp;FMT=ABS&amp;FMTS=ABS:FT&amp;type=current&amp;date=Jan+03%2C+1986&amp;author=The+Los+Angeles+Times&amp;pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&amp;desc=Douglas+Wins+%243.4B+Pact+to+Build+C-17&amp;pqatl=google |title = Douglas Wins $3.4B Pact to Build C-17 |publisher = Los Angeles Times |date = 3 January 1986}}&lt;/ref&gt; Development problems and limited funding caused delays in the late 1980s.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://rtoc.ida.org/rtoc/open/briefings_articles/kennednd.pdf |title = Historical Realities of C-17 Program Pose Challenge for Future Acquisitions |first = Betty Raab |last = Kennedy |publisher = Institute for Defense Analyses |date=December 1999}}&lt;/ref&gt; Criticisms were made of the developing aircraft and questions were raised about more cost-effective alternatives during this time.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/24563333.html?dids=24563333:24563333&amp;FMT=ABS&amp;FMTS=ABS:FT&amp;type=current&amp;date=Sep+09%2C+1989&amp;author=Col.+Richard+L.+Fuller%2C+Director+of+public+affairs%2C+United+States+Air+Force.&amp;pub=Chicago+Tribune+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&amp;desc=More+load+for+the+buck+with+C-17&amp;pqatl=google |title = More load for the buck with C-17 |first = Richard L. |last = Fuller |publisher = Chicago Tribune |date = 9 September 1989}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&amp;p_theme=sl&amp;p_action=search&amp;p_maxdocs=200&amp;p_topdoc=1&amp;p_text_direct-0=0EB04C1540E361A8&amp;p_field_direct-0=document_id&amp;p_perpage=10&amp;p_sort=YMD_date:D&amp;s_trackval=GooglePM |title = McDonnell Plugs Away on C-17 |publisher = St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date = 3 April 1989}}&lt;/ref&gt; In April 1990, Defense Secretary [[Dick Cheney]] reduced the order from 210 to 120 aircraft.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://news.google.co.uk/newspapers?id=mjIhAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=DlcEAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=6844,2683814&amp;dq=usaf+c-17&amp;hl=en |title = Cheney cuts back on Air Force programs |first = Eliot |last = Brenner |publisher = Bryan Times |date = 26 April 1990}}&lt;/ref&gt; The C-17's maiden flight was on 15 September 1991 from the McDonnell Douglas west coast plant in [[Long Beach, California]], about a year behind schedule.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/17/us/c-17-s-first-flight-smoother-than-debate.html |title = C-17's First Flight Smoother Than Debate |publisher = New York Times |date = 17 September 1991}}&lt;/ref&gt; The first aircraft (T-1) and five more production models (P1-P5) participated in extensive flight testing and evaluation at [[Edwards Air Force Base]].&lt;ref name=&quot;RL30685&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://opencrs.com/document/RL30685 RL30685 |title = Military Airlift: C-17 Aircraft Program |publisher = Congressional Research Service |date = 5 June 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; Two complete airframes were built for static and dynamic load testing.&lt;ref name=&quot;Aeroflight&quot;&gt;[http://www.aeroflight.co.uk/aircraft/types/boeing-c-17-globemaster-iii.htm &quot;Boeing C-17 Globemaster III Aircraft Profile&quot;] Aeroflight&lt;/ref&gt;

The C-17 received the &quot;Globemaster III&quot; name in early 1993.&lt;ref name=&quot;norton p12-3&quot;/&gt; In late 1993, the DoD gave the contractor two years to solve production and cost overrun problems or face termination of the contract after the delivery of the 40th aircraft.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/24383613.html?dids=24383613:24383613&amp;FMT=ABS&amp;FMTS=ABS:FT&amp;type=current&amp;date=Mar+29%2C+1993&amp;author=David+Evans%2C+Chicago+Tribune.&amp;pub=Chicago+Tribune+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&amp;desc=Pentagon+to+Air+Force%3A+C-17+flunks&amp;pqatl=google |title = Pentagon to Air Force: C-17 flunks |first = David |last = Evans |publisher = Chicago Tribune |date = 29 March 1993}}&lt;/ref&gt; By accepting the 1993 terms, McDonnell Douglas incurred a loss of nearly US$1.5 billion on the development phase of the program.&lt;ref name=&quot;RL30685&quot;/&gt;

[[File:Air force globemasters unload supplies in mississippi aug 31 2005.jpg|thumb|Three C-17s unload supplies to help victims of [[Hurricane Katrina]] at [[Keesler Air Force Base]], [[Mississippi]], in August 2005.|alt=Vehicles and personnel unloading supplies from three gray C-17s parked together for victims of Hurricane Katrina.]]

In April 1994, the C-17 program was still over budget, and did not meet weight, fuel burn, payload and range specifications. It also failed several key criteria and tests that had been conducted to evaluate its airworthiness.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19910528&amp;slug=1285732 |title = Air Force Letter To Douglas Spells Out 75 Defects For C-17 |publisher = Los Angeles Times |date = 28 May 1991}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&amp;p_theme=lb&amp;p_action=search&amp;p_maxdocs=200&amp;p_topdoc=1&amp;p_text_direct-0=0EAE8F93D6E54ED8&amp;p_field_direct-0=document_id&amp;p_perpage=10&amp;p_sort=YMD_date:D&amp;s_trackval=GooglePM |title = C-17 fails engine start test |publisher = Press-Telegram |date = 12 April 1994}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CO&amp;s_site=charlotte&amp;p_multi=CO&amp;p_theme=realcities&amp;p_action=search&amp;p_maxdocs=200&amp;p_topdoc=1&amp;p_text_direct-0=0EB6CC1343F2E14F&amp;p_field_direct-0=document_id&amp;p_perpage=10&amp;p_sort=YMD_date:D&amp;s_trackval=GooglePM |title = Parts Orders for C-17 far too high, GAO says |publisher = Charlotte Observer |date = 16 March 1994}}&lt;/ref&gt; Airflow over the aircraft caused problems with parachutes and there were other technical problems with mission software, landing gear, and so on.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://archive.gao.gov/t2pbat3/151473.pdf |title = The C-17 Proposed Settlement and Program Update |publisher = United States General Accounting Office |date = 28 April 1994}}&lt;/ref&gt; In May 1994, a proposal to cut the aircraft's production numbers to as low as 32 planes emerged, but was rescinded.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sandiego/access/1242506621.html?dids=1242506621:1242506621&amp;FMT=ABS&amp;FMTS=ABS:FT&amp;type=current&amp;date=May+25%2C+1994&amp;author=OTTO+KREISHER&amp;pub=The+San+Diego+Union+-+Tribune&amp;desc=House+rescinds+cuts+in+C-17+program+%7C+Vote+may+help+thousands+retain+jobs+in+Long+Beach&amp;pqatl=google |title = House rescinds cuts in C-17 program |first = Otto |last = Kreisher |publisher = San Diego Union |date = 25 May 1994}}&lt;/ref&gt; A July 1994 GAO document revealed that to justify investing in the C-17 rather than in the C-5, Air Force and DoD studies from 1986 and 1991 had claimed that the C-17 could use 6,400 more runways outside the U.S. than the C-5; it was later discovered that this study had only considered the runway dimensions, but not their strength or Load Classification Numbers (LCN). The C-5 has a lower LCN than the C-17, although the U.S. Air Force places both in the same broad Load Classification Group (LCG). When considering runway dimensions and their load ratings, the C-17's worldwide runway advantage over the C-5 shrank from 6,400 to 911 airfields.&lt;ref name=&quot;airfields&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://archive.gao.gov/t2pbat3/152088.pdf |title = Comparison of C-5 and C-17 Airfield Availability |publisher = United States General Accounting Office |date=July 1994}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, the C-17's ability to use lower quality, austere airfields was not considered.&lt;ref name=&quot;airfields&quot;/&gt;

A January 1995 GAO report revealed that while the original C-17 budget was US$41.8 billion for 210 aircraft, the 120 aircraft already ordered at that point had already cost US$39.5 billion.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.gao.gov/archive/1995/ns95026.pdf |title = C-17 Aircraft – Cost and Performance Issues |publisher = United States General Accounting Office |date=January 1995}}&lt;/ref&gt; In March 1994, the U.S. Army had decided it no longer needed the {{convert|60000|lb|abbr=on}} [[Low Altitude Parachute Extraction System]] (LAPES) delivery that the C-17 was supposed to provide, feeling that the {{convert|42000|lb|abbr=on}} capability of the C-130 Hercules was sufficient. It was decided not to conduct C-17 LAPES training beyond the testing of a {{convert|42000|lb|abbr=on}} LAPES delivery. There were still airflow problems that prevented the C-17 from meeting its airdrop requirements. A February 1997 GAO Report revealed that a C-17 with a full payload could not land on {{convert|3000|ft|-2|abbr=on}} wet runways, for simulations suggested {{convert|5000|ft|abbr=on}} was required.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.gao.gov/archive/1997/ns97050.pdf |title = C-17 Globemaster – Support of Operation Joint Endevour |publisher = United States General Accounting Office |date=February 1997}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[McDonnell Douglas YC-15|YC-15]] was transferred out of [[Pima Air &amp; Space Museum]] to [[309th Aerospace Maintenance and Regeneration Group|AMARC]] to be made flightworthy again for further flight tests for the C-17 program in March 1997.&lt;ref name=&quot;BFS&quot;&gt;{{cite book|author=Bonny, Danny; Barry Fryer; and Martyn Swann |title=AMARC MASDC III, The Aerospace Maintenance and Regeneration Center, Davis-Monthan AFB, AZ, 1997–2005 |publisher=British Aviation Research Group, |location = Surry, England |year=2006 |isbn=0-906339-07-3, 978-0-906339-07-7 |page=65}}&lt;/ref&gt;

By the mid-1990s, most of the problems had been resolved.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.afa.org/media/press/windall.asp |title = Air Force Secretary Says Modernization, C-17 on Track |publisher = Air Force magazine |date = 19 September 1995}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LB&amp;p_theme=lb&amp;p_action=search&amp;p_maxdocs=200&amp;p_topdoc=1&amp;p_text_direct-0=0EAE901FCF584869&amp;p_field_direct-0=document_id&amp;p_perpage=10&amp;p_sort=YMD_date:D&amp;s_trackval=GooglePM |title = Future Brightens for C-17 Program |publisher = Press-Telegram |date = 31 March 1995}}&lt;/ref&gt; The first C-17 squadron was declared operational by the U.S. Air Force in January 1995.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&amp;p_theme=sl&amp;p_action=search&amp;p_maxdocs=200&amp;p_topdoc=1&amp;p_text_direct-0=0EB082E680DBFA28&amp;p_field_direct-0=document_id&amp;p_perpage=10&amp;p_sort=YMD_date:D&amp;s_trackval=GooglePM |title = Air Force fills Squadron of C-17s |publisher = Associated Press |date = 18 January 1995}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1996, DoD ordered another 80 aircraft for a total of 120.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/17166359.html?dids=17166359:17166359&amp;FMT=ABS&amp;FMTS=ABS:FT&amp;type=current&amp;date=Jun+01%2C+1996&amp;author=Michael+Kilian%2C+Washington+Bureau.&amp;pub=Chicago+Tribune+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&amp;desc=IN+RECORD+PROCUREMENT+U.S.+ORDERS+80+C-17S+PLANE+DEAL+GOOD+FOR+2%2C000+JOBS+IN+CALIFORNIA&amp;pqatl=google |title = In Record Procurement U.S. Orders 80 C17s – Plane Good Deal for 2,000 jobs in California |first = Michael |last = Kilian |publisher = Chicago Tribune |date = 1 July 1996}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1997 McDonnell Douglas merged with its former competitor, Boeing. In April 1999, Boeing proposed to cut the price of the C-17 if the Air Force bought 60 more,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-64094695.html |title = Boeing to cut price of C-17 if Air Force buys 60 more |first = James |last = Wallace |publisher = Seattle Post |date = 2 April 1999}}&lt;/ref&gt; and in August 2002, the order was increased to 180 aircraft.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/16/business/9.7-billion-us-deal-for-boeing-c-17-s.html |title = $9.7 Billion U.S. Deal for Boeing C-17's |publisher = New York Times |date = 16 August 2002}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Design==
[[File:C-17 OtwartaRampa.jpg|thumb|Interior of a C-17|alt=The rear cargo door of a C-17 is opening, revealing the huge interior volume of the aircraft.]]

The C-17 is {{convert|174|ft|m}} long and has a wingspan of about {{convert|170|ft|m}}. It can airlift cargo fairly close to a battle area. The size and weight of U.S. mechanized firepower and equipment have grown in recent decades from increased air mobility requirements, particularly for large or heavy non-palletized [[outsize cargo]].

The C-17 is powered by four fully [[Thrust reversal|reversible]], [[Pratt &amp; Whitney PW2000|F117-PW-100]] [[turbofan]] engines (the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] designation for the commercial Pratt and Whitney PW2040, used on the [[Boeing 757]]). Each engine is rated at 40,400&amp;nbsp;lb&lt;sub&gt;f&lt;/sub&gt; (180&amp;nbsp;kN) of [[thrust]]. The thrust reversers direct air upward and forward, reducing the chance of [[foreign object damage]] and providing enough thrust to back the aircraft on the ground. The thrust reversers can also be used in flight at idle-reverse for added drag in maximum-rate descents.

[[File:C-17 no169 landing.jpg|thumb|left|C-17 landing, showing its landing gear]]

The aircraft requires a crew of three (pilot, copilot, and loadmaster) for cargo operations. Cargo is loaded through a large aft ramp that accommodates rolling stock, such a 69-ton (63-metric ton) [[M1 Abrams]] tank, other armored vehicles, trucks, and trailers, along with palletized cargo. The cargo compartment is 88 feet (26.82 m) long by 18 feet (5.49 m) wide by 12 feet 4&amp;nbsp;inches (3.76 m) high. The cargo floor has rollers for palletized cargo that can be flipped to provide a flat floor suitable for rolling stock.

Maximum payload of the C-17 is 170,900&amp;nbsp;lb (77,500&amp;nbsp;kg), and its [[Maximum Takeoff Weight]] is 585,000&amp;nbsp;lb (265,350&amp;nbsp;kg). With a payload of 160,000&amp;nbsp;lb (72,600&amp;nbsp;kg) and an initial cruise altitude of 28,000&amp;nbsp;ft (8,500 m), the C-17 has an unrefueled range of about 2,400 nautical miles (4,400&amp;nbsp;km) on the first 71 aircraft, and 2,800 nautical miles (5,200&amp;nbsp;km) on all subsequent extended-range models that include sealed center wing bay as a fuel tank. Boeing informally calls these planes the ''C-17 ER''.&lt;ref name=&quot;bids_c17_fml&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.boeing.com/commercial/airports/arff/arffc17.pdf |title = C-17/C-17 ER Flammable Material Locations |publisher = Boeing |date = 1 May 2005}}&lt;/ref&gt; The C-17's cruise speed is about 450 knots (833&amp;nbsp;km/h) (0.76 Mach).&lt;ref name=AF_fact/&gt; The C-17 is designed to airdrop 102 [[paratrooper]]s and their equipment. The U.S. Army [[BCT Ground Combat Vehicle Program|BCT Ground Combat Vehicle]] is to be transported by the C-17.

[[File:C17 Reverse Thrust.JPG|thumb|A C-17 creates a visible [[vortex]] while using [[Thrust reversal|reverse thrust]] to push the aircraft backwards on a runway.]]

The C-17 is designed to operate from runways as short as 3,500&amp;nbsp;ft (1,064 m) and as narrow as 90&amp;nbsp;ft (27 m). In addition, the C-17 can operate from unpaved, unimproved runways (although with greater chance of damage to the aircraft).&lt;ref name=AF_fact /&gt; The thrust reversers can be used to back the aircraft and reverse direction on narrow taxiways using a three- (or more) point turn.&lt;ref name=AF_fact /&gt;

==Operational history==
===United States Air Force===

The first production model was delivered to [[Charleston Air Force Base]], [[South Carolina]] on 14 July 1993. The first squadron of C-17s, the [[17th Airlift Squadron]], was declared operationally ready on 17 January 1995.&lt;ref name=&quot;nort_units&quot;&gt;Norton 2001, pp. 94–95.&lt;/ref&gt; The C-17 has broken 22 records for oversized payloads.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.boeing.com/defense-space/military/c17/news/2001/q4/nr_011128n.htm |title = Boeing C-17 Globemaster III Claims 13 World Records |publisher = Boeing |date = 28 November 2001}}&lt;/ref&gt; The C-17 was awarded US aviation's most prestigious award, the [[Collier Trophy]] in 1994.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.naa.aero/html/awards/index.cfm?cmsid=150 |title = Collier Trophy, 1990–1999 winners |publisher = National Aeronautic Association |accessdate = 1-04-2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:C-17 4.jpg|thumb|left|A USAF C-17 takes off]]

The Air Force originally programmed to buy a total of 120 C-17s, with the last one being scheduled for delivery in November 2004. The fiscal 2000 budget funded another 14 aircraft, primarily for [[Air Mobility Command]] (AMC) support of the [[United States Special Operations Command]] (USSOCOM). Basing of the original 120 C-17s was with the [[437th Airlift Wing]] and [[315th Airlift Wing]] at Charleston AFB, South Carolina, the [[62nd Airlift Wing]] and [[446th Airlift Wing]] at [[McChord Air Force Base]], Washington (first aircraft arrived in July 1999), the [[Air Education and Training Command]]'s (AETC) [[97th Air Mobility Wing]] at [[Altus Air Force Base|Altus AFB]], Oklahoma, and the [[Air Mobility Command]]-gained [[172nd Airlift Wing]] of the [[Mississippi Air National Guard]] at [[Jackson-Evers International Airport]]/ANGB, Mississippi. Although operationally-gained by the [[Air Mobility Command]], the C-17 aircraft assigned to the 172 AW are the only C-17s strictly under direct control of the [[Air National Guard]] (ANG).

[[File:Presidential limousine loaded in aircraft.jpg|thumb|On both domestic and foreign trips, the US [[Presidential state car (United States)|Presidential Limousine]] is transported in a [[C-17 Globemaster III]].]]

Basing of the additional 13 aircraft went to the [[305th Air Mobility Wing]] and [[514th Air Mobility Wing]] at [[McGuire Air Force Base]], New Jersey; the [[3rd Wing]] and [[176th Wing]] at [[Elmendorf Air Force Base]], Alaska; [[15th Airlift Wing]] and [[154th Wing]] at [[Hickam Air Force Base]], Hawaii; and [[60th Air Mobility Wing]] and [[349th Air Mobility Wing]] at [[Travis Air Force Base]], California. An additional 60 units were ordered in May 2002. In FY 2006, eight C-17s were delivered to [[March Joint Air Reserve Base]], California. Although operationally-gained by the [[Air Mobility Command]], these C-17s are the only aircraft strictly under direct control of the [[Air Force Reserve Command]] (AFRC). In 2007, Congress appropriated funds for 10 additional USAF C-17s, bringing the total planned fleet size (on order + delivered) to 190. Additional aircraft were subsequently assigned to [[Dover Air Force Base]], Delaware which had previously been strictly equipped with [[C-5 Galaxy]] aircraft.

[[File:Pzh-2000 inside of a C-17.jpg|thumb|left|USAF C-17 transporting a Dutch [[Panzerhaubitze 2000|PzH 2000]] self-propelled howitzer into Afghanistan, September 2006.]]

The C-17 have been, and continue to be, used to deliver military goods and [[humanitarian aid]] during [[Operation Enduring Freedom]] in [[Afghanistan]] as well as [[Iraq War|Operation Iraqi Freedom]] in [[Iraq]]. On 26 March 2003, 15 USAF C-17s participated in the biggest combat airdrop since the [[United States invasion of Panama]] in December 1989: the night-time airdrop of 1,000 paratroopers from the [[173rd Airborne Brigade Combat Team (United States)|173rd Airborne Brigade]] occurred over Bashur, [[Iraq]]. It opened the northern front to combat operations and constituted the largest formation airdrop carried out by the United States since World War II. USAF C-17s have also been used to assist US allies transport military equipment, including Canadian armored vehicles to Afghanistan in 2003 and the redeployment of Australian forces in Australia and the Solomon Islands during the [[Operation Astute|Australian-led military deployment to East Timor]] in 2006. In late September and early November 2006, USAF C-17s flew 15 Canadian [[Leopard_1#Canada2|Leopard C2 tanks]] from Kyrgyzstan into Kandahar in support of the Afghanistan NATO mission.

A C-17 also accompanies the President of the United States on his visits to both domestic and foreign arrangements, consultations, and meetings. The C-17 is used to transport the [[Presidential State Car (United States)|Presidential Limousine]] and security detachments.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&amp;p_multi=APAB&amp;d_place=APAB&amp;p_theme=newslibrary2&amp;p_action=search&amp;p_maxdocs=200&amp;p_topdoc=1&amp;p_text_direct-0=10526128375A9604&amp;p_field_direct-0=document_id&amp;p_perpage=10&amp;p_sort=YMD_date:D&amp;s_trackval=GooglePM |title = New Mexico Airport runway damaged by President's Cargo Plane |publisher = Associated Press |date = 1 September 2004}}&lt;/ref&gt; There have been several occasions where a C-17 has been used to transport the President himself, temporarily gaining the [[Air Force One]] callsign while doing so.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PD&amp;s_site=twincities&amp;p_multi=SP&amp;p_theme=realcities&amp;p_action=search&amp;p_maxdocs=200&amp;p_topdoc=1&amp;p_text_direct-0=0EDCB9D2E176DD80&amp;p_field_direct-0=document_id&amp;p_perpage=10&amp;p_sort=YMD_date:D&amp;s_trackval=GooglePM |title = C-17 proves its worth in Bosnian Supply effort |publisher = St Paul Pioneer |date = 16 February 1996}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:C-17 Airdrop 4 Humvees + 50 Paratroopers.ogv|thumb|thumbtime=2|right|C-17s from the 517th Airlift Squadron dropping equipment and airborne infantry during joint training in September 2010.]]

There has been debate about follow-on orders for the C-17, with the Air Force requesting line shutdown, and members of [[United States Congress|Congress]] attempting to reinstate production. Furthermore, in [[Fiscal year|FY]]2007, the Air Force requested $1.6 billion to deal with what it termed &quot;excessive combat use&quot; on operational airframes.&lt;ref name=&quot;avweek_20060313&quot;&gt;{{cite web |coauthors = Fulghum, D., Butler, A., Barrie, D. |publisher = ''[[Aviation Week &amp; Space Technology]]'' |date = 13 March 2006 |page = 43 |url = http://www.aviationnow.com/search/AvnowSearchResult.do?reference=xml/awst_xml/2006/03/13/AW_03_13_2006_p43-01.xml |title = Boeing's C-17 wins against EADS' A400}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, in testimony before a House of Representatives subcommittee on air and land forces, General [[Arthur Lichte]], USAF, the Commander of [[Air Mobility Command]] indicated extending production to another 15 aircraft, bringing the total to 205. Pending the delivery of the results of two studies in 2009, Lichte considers that the Air Force may have to keep the production line open for purchase of even more C-17s to satisfy airlift requirements.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2008/04/04/222723/usaf-reveals-c-17-cracks-and-dispute-on-production-future.html |title = USAF reveals C-17 cracks and dispute on production future |first = Stephen |last = Trimble |publisher = Flightglobal.com |date = 4 April 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===United Kingdom===

Boeing has marketed the C-17 to many European nations including Belgium, Germany, France, Italy, Spain and the United Kingdom. The [[Royal Air Force]] has established an aim of having interoperability and some weapons and capabilities commonality with the [[United States Air Force]]. The UK's 1998 [[Strategic Defence Review]] identified a requirement for a strategic airlifter. The Short-Term Strategic Airlift (STSA) competition commenced in September of that year, however tendering was canceled in August 1999 with some bids identified by ministers as too expensive, including the Boeing/[[British Aerospace|BAe]] C-17 bid, and others unsuitable.&lt;ref name=&quot;business&quot;&gt;{{cite news |first = Dominic |last = O'Connell |title = Political clash haunts MoD deal decision |work = The Business |publisher = Sunday Business Group |date= 5 December 1999}}&lt;/ref&gt; The project continued, with the C-17 seen as the favorite.&lt;ref name=&quot;business&quot;/&gt; In the light of continuing delays to the [[Airbus A400M]] program, the UK [[Secretary of State for Defence|Defence Secretary]], [[Geoff Hoon]], announced in May 2000 that the RAF would lease four C-17s at an annual cost of [[Pound sterling|£]]100 million&lt;ref name=&quot;avweek_20060313&quot;/&gt; from Boeing for an initial seven years with an optional two year extension. At this point the RAF would have the option to buy the aircraft or return them to Boeing. The UK committed to upgrading the C-17s inline with the USAF so that in the event of their being returned to Boeing the USAF could adopt them.

The first C-17 was delivered to the RAF at Boeing's Long Beach facility on 17 May 2001 and flown to [[RAF Brize Norton]] by a crew from [[No. 99 Squadron RAF|No. 99 Squadron]] which had previously trained with USAF crews to gain competence on the type. The RAF's fourth C-17 was delivered on 24 August 2001. The RAF aircraft were some of the first to take advantage of the new center wing fuel tank found in Block 13 aircraft. In RAF service, the C-17 has not been given an [[British military aircraft designation systems|official designation]] (for example,, C-130J referred to as Hercules C4 or C5), but is referred to simply as the C-17 or &quot;C-17A Globemaster&quot;.

[[File:Royal Air Force C-17 August 2010.jpg|thumb|RAF C-17 at RAF Lakenheath, August 2010.]]
The RAF declared itself delighted with the C-17. Although the Globemaster fleet was to be a fallback for the A400M, the UK announced on 21 July 2004 that they had elected to buy their four C-17s at the end of the lease, even though the A400M appeared to be moving closer to production. They also announced there would be a follow-on order for one C-17, with possible additional purchases later.&lt;ref name=&quot;gdr_2003&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.global-defence.com/2003/globe_master.htm |title = RAF's Globe Master |publisher = ''[[Global Defence Review]]'' |year =  2003}}&lt;/ref&gt; While the A400M is described as a &quot;strategic&quot; airlifter, the C-17 gives the RAF true strategic capabilities that it would not wish to lose, for example a maximum payload of 169,500&amp;nbsp;lb (77,000&amp;nbsp;kg) compared to the Airbus' 82,000&amp;nbsp;lb (37,000&amp;nbsp;kg).&lt;ref name=&quot;avweek_20060313&quot;/&gt;

The [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] (MoD) announced on 4 August 2006 that they had ordered an additional C-17 and that the four aircraft on lease would be purchased at the end of the current contract in 2008. A fifth aircraft was delivered on 22 February 2008 and reported for duty on 7 April 2008 at [[RAF Brize Norton|Brize Norton air base]] in [[Oxfordshire]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2008/04/07/222815/pictures-uk-receives-fifth-c-17-as-raf-fleet-passes-40000-flight.html |title = UK receives fifth C-17, as RAF fleet passes 40,000 flight hours |first = Craig |last = Hoyle |publisher = ''FlightGlobal.com'' |date = 14 April 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; Due to fears that the A400M may suffer further delays, the MoD announced in 2006 that it planned to acquire three more C-17s, for a total of eight, with delivery in 2009–2010. On 26 July 2007, Defence Secretary [[Des Browne]] announced that the MoD intended to order a sixth C-17 to boost operations in Iraq and Afghanistan.&lt;ref name=&quot;UK_6th&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/EquipmentAndLogistics/BrownePurchaseOfExtraC17WillsignificantlyBoostUkMilitaryOperations.htm |title = Browne: Purchase of extra C-17 will 'significantly boost' UK military operations |publisher = UK Ministry of Defence |date = 27 July 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; On 3 December 2007, the MoD announced a contract for a sixth C-17,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/EquipmentAndLogistics/RafGetsSixthC17Globemaster.htm |title = RAF gets sixth C-17 Globemaster |publisher = UK Ministry of Defence |date = 4 December 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; which was received on 11 June 2008.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.boeing.com/news/releases/2008/q2/080611c_nr.html |title = Boeing Delivers 6th C-17 to Royal Air Force |publisher = Boeing |date = 11 June 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On 18 December 2009, Boeing confirmed that the RAF had ordered a seventh C-17,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.airforcesmonthly.com/view_news.asp?ID=1298 |title = RAF to get 7th C-17 |publisher =  AirForces Monthly |date = 18 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=7th_C-17&gt;{{cite web |url = http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&amp;item=1000 |title = Royal Air Force to Acquire 7th Boeing C-17 Globemaster III |publisher =  Boeing |date = 17 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; which was delivered on 16 November 2010.&lt;ref name=&quot;RAF_Boeing_C-17s&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&amp;item=1523 |title = Boeing Delivers UK Royal Air Force's 7th C-17 Globemaster III |publisher = Boeing |date = 16 Nov 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Boeing briefed the MoD in November 2010 regarding the possible acquisition of an eighth C-17, but no decision has been made. Production will be slowing down in order to extend the time before the C-17 production line has to shut down.&lt;ref name=&quot;UK_8th&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_channel.jsp?channel=defense&amp;id=news/asd/2010/11/18/02.xml&amp;headline=London%20Unofficially%20Eyes%20Eighth%20Boeing%20C-17 |title = London Unofficially Eyes Eighth Boeing C-17 |publisher = AviationWeek |date = 18 Nov 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Australia===
[[File:RAAF C-17 Afghanistan.jpg|thumb|An RAAF C-17 in Afghanistan, Dec 2010.]]

The [[Royal Australian Air Force]] (RAAF) began investigating options to acquire heavy lift transport aircraft for strategic transport in 2005.&lt;ref name=&quot;McLaughlin_40-41&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |last=McLaughlin |first=Andrew |date=September 2008 |title=Big Mover |journal=Australian Aviation |publisher=Phantom Media |location=Canberra |volume= |pages=40–41}}&lt;/ref&gt; In late 2005 the then [[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for Defence]] [[Robert Hill (Australian diplomat)|Robert Hill]] stated that the [[Australian Defence Force]] was considering such aircraft due to the limited availability of strategic airlift aircraft from partner nations and air freight companies. The C-17 was considered to be favoured over the A400M as it was a &quot;proven aircraft&quot; and was already in production. One major requirement from the RAAF was the ability to airlift the [[Australian Army|Army's]] new [[M1 Abrams]] [[main battle tank]]s; another requirement was immediate delivery. Though unstated, commonality with the USAF and the United Kingdom's RAF was also considered advantageous. The aircraft for the RAAF were ordered directly from the USAF production run, and are identical to American C-17 even in paint scheme, the only difference being the [[Military aircraft insignia|national marking]]s. This allowed delivery to commence within nine months of commitment to the program.&lt;ref name=&quot;awst_20061211&quot;&gt;&quot;Stock Standard&quot;. ''[[Aviation Week &amp; Space Technology]]. 11 December 2006.&lt;/ref&gt;

On 2 March 2006, the Australian Government announced the purchase of three aircraft and one option with an entry into service date of 2006.&lt;ref name=&quot;avweek_20060313&quot;/&gt; In July 2006 a fixed price contract was awarded to Boeing to deliver four C-17s for US$780m (AUD$1bn).&lt;ref name=&quot;reuters_20060731&quot;&gt;&quot;[http://today.reuters.com/business/newsarticle.aspx?type=tnBusinessNews&amp;storyID=nN31354114&amp;imageid=∩= Boeing wins $780 mln deal for Australia C-17s].&quot; ''[[Reuters]]''. 31 July 2006.&lt;/ref&gt; Australia also signed a US$80.7M contract to join the global 'virtual fleet' C-17 sustainment program&lt;ref name=&quot;McLaughlin_42&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |last=McLaughlin |first=Andrew|year= 2008 |title= Big Mover |journal=Australian Aviation |publisher=Phantom Media |location=Canberra |volume=September 2008 |page=42}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the RAAF's C-17s will receive the same upgrades as the USAF's fleet.&lt;ref name=&quot;McLaughlin_46&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |last= McLaughlin |first= Andrew |year= 2008 |title= Big Mover |journal= Australian Aviation |publisher= Phantom Media |location=Canberra |volume= September 2008 |page=46}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:02-corbould.jpg|thumb|left|Wing Commander [[Linda Corbould]], commander of [[No. 36 Squadron RAAF]], training in a USAF C-17]]

The Royal Australian Air Force took delivery of its first C-17 in a ceremony at Boeing's plant at Long Beach, California on 28 November 2006.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url=http://www.boeing.com/defense-space/military/c17/news/2006/q4/061128b_nr.html |title=Boeing Delivers Royal Australian Air Force's First C-17 |work=Boeing |date= 28 November 2010 |accessdate=13 August 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Several days later the aircraft flew from [[Hickam Air Force Base]], [[Honolulu|Honolulu, Hawaii]] to [[Fairbairn, Canberra|Defence Establishment Fairbairn]], [[Canberra]], arriving on 4 December 2006. The aircraft was formally accepted in a ceremony at Fairbairn shortly after arrival.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.minister.defence.gov.au/NelsonMintpl.cfm?CurrentId=6212 |title=First C-17 arrives in Australia |accessdate=11 July 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; The second aircraft was delivered to the RAAF on 11 May 2007 and the third was delivered on 18 December 2007. The fourth Australian C-17 was delivered on 19 January 2008.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite press release |title=Air Force's C-17 fleet delivered on time, on budget |publisher=[[Greg Combet|The Hon. Greg Combet MP, Parliamentary Secretary for Defence Procurement]] |date=18 January 2008 |url=http://www.minister.defence.gov.au/Combettpl.cfm?CurrentId=7388 |format= |accessdate=27 January 2008 |quote= }}&lt;/ref&gt; All the Australian C-17s are operated by [[No. 36 Squadron RAAF|No. 36 Squadron]] and are based at [[RAAF Base Amberley]] in Queensland.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.raaf.gov.au/aircraft/globemaster.htm|title=C-17 Globemaster heavy transport |publisher=Royal Australian Air Force |accessdate=14 September 2008 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080329050815/http://www.raaf.gov.au/aircraft/globemaster.htm |archivedate = March 29, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; The squadron is working towards reaching its full operational capability in mid-2011.&lt;ref name=&quot;McLaughlin_42&quot; /&gt;

Australia's C-17s have supported ADF operations around the world. Tasks have included supporting [[Air Combat Group RAAF|Air Combat Group]] training deployments to the United States, transporting [[Royal Australian Navy]] [[Sikorsky S-70|Sea Hawk]] helicopters and making fortnightly missions to the Middle East to supply Australian forces in Iraq and Afghanistan.

The C-17s have also carried humanitarian supplies to [[Papua New Guinea]] during [[Operation Papua New Guinea Assist]] in 2007, supplies and South African [[Aérospatiale Puma|Puma helicopters]] to [[Burma]] in 2008 following [[Cyclone Nargis]],&lt;ref name=&quot;McLaughlin_45&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |last=McLaughlin |first=Andrew |year=2008 |title=Big Mover |journal=Australian Aviation |publisher=Phantom Media |location=Canberra |volume=September 2008 |page=45}}&lt;/ref&gt; relief supplies to [[Samoa]] following the [[2009 Samoa earthquake|2009 earthquake]], relief supplies around Queensland following the [[2010–2011 Queensland floods|2010-2011 floods]] and [[Cyclone Yasi]], and rescue teams and equipment to [[New Zealand]] following the [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]], and delivery of equipment for mitigation of the effects caused by the [[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami]] from Western Australia to Japan.

===Canada===
[[File:080831-F-0929W-423.JPG|thumb|Canadian Forces C-17 (CC-177) at Lake Front Airport, New Orleans]]

Canada has had a long-standing need for strategic airlift for humanitarian and military operations around the world {{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}. The [[Canadian Forces]] (CF) had followed a pattern similar to the [[Luftwaffe]] in using rented [[Antonov]]s and [[Ilyushin]]s for many of their needs, including deploying the [[Disaster Assistance Response Team]] (DART) to tsunami-stricken [[Sri Lanka]] in 2005. The CF was forced to rely entirely on leased [[Antonov An-124|An-124 ''Ruslan'']] for a [[Operation Halo|deployment to Haiti]] in 2003,{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} as well as a combination of leased ''Ruslans'', Ilyushins and USAF C-17s for moving heavy equipment into [[Afghanistan]]. The Canadian Forces Future Strategic Airlifter Project was initiated in 2002 to study alternatives, including long-term leasing arrangements.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ploughshares.ca/libraries/monitor/monj05g.htm &quot;Strategic lift capacity for Canada&quot;]. The Ploughshares Monitor, 2005.&lt;/ref&gt;

On 5 July 2006, the Canadian government issued a notice that it intended to negotiate directly with Boeing for the purchase of four airlifters.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.merx.com/English/SUPPLIER_Menu.Asp?WCE=Show&amp;TAB=1&amp;State=7&amp;id=PW-%24SSC-004-13706&amp;hcode=lZi0smL%2fmio4eGxwwqDpfg%3d%3d  Airlift Capability Project – Strategic ACP-S – ACAN] MERX Website – Government of Canada&lt;/ref&gt; Then on 1 February 2007 Canada awarded a contract for four C-17s with delivery beginning in August 2007.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070202/oconnor_plane_070202/20070202?hub=Canada &quot;O'Connor announces military plane purchase&quot;. CTV.ca, 2 February 2007.]&lt;/ref&gt; Like Australia, Canada was granted airframes originally slated for the U.S. Air Force, to accelerate delivery.&lt;ref name=&quot;fi_20070205&quot;&gt;[http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2007/02/05/211969/canada-gets-usaf-slots-for-august-delivery-after-signing-for-four-boeing-c-17-in-20-year-c4bn.html &quot;Canada gets USAF slots for August delivery after signing for four Boeing C-17 in 20-year C$4bn deal, settles provincial workshare quabble&quot;]. Wastnage, J. ''[[Flight International]]''. 5 February 2007.&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Globemaster 0026.jpg|thumb|left|Canadian Forces CC-177 Globemaster on approach to CFB Trenton]]

On 16 June 2007, the first Canadian C-17 (designated the CC-177 by the [[Canadian Forces]]) rolled off the assembly line at Long Beach, California and into the paint hangar for painting and addition of Canadian markings including the national logo and air force [[roundel]]. The first Canadian C-17 made its initial flight on 23 July.&lt;ref&gt;[http://boeingnews.web.boeing.com/archive/07_07/072507/070725a_c17_p2.html &quot;Canada One C-17 makes first flight&quot;]. Boeing, 25 July 2007.&lt;/ref&gt; It was turned over to Canada on 8 August,&lt;ref name=&quot;CF_C-17&quot;/&gt; and participated at the [[Abbotsford International Airshow]] on 11 August prior to arriving at its new home base at 8 Wing, [[CFB Trenton]], Ontario on 12 August.&lt;ref name=&quot;Trenton&quot;&gt;[http://www.airforce.forces.gc.ca/site/newsroom/news_e.asp?id=4120 &quot;First CC-177 Globemaster III Receives Patriotic and Enthusiastic Welcome&quot;]. Department of National Defence.&lt;/ref&gt; Its first operational mission was delivery of disaster relief to [[Jamaica]] in the aftermath of [[Hurricane Dean]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070824/globemaster_070824/20070824?hub=Canada &quot;New military aircraft leaves on aid mission&quot;]. ''Cnews.com'', 24 August 2007.&lt;/ref&gt; The second C-17 arrived at 8 Wing, CFB Trenton on 18 October 2007. The last of four aircraft was delivered in April 2008.&lt;ref name=&quot;CF_4th&quot;&gt;[http://www.airforce.forces.gc.ca/site/newsroom/news_e.asp?cat=114&amp;id=5802 &quot;Canada takes delivery of final CC-177&quot;]. Canadian Forces, 3 April 2008.&lt;/ref&gt; The C-17 is officially designated ''CC-177 Globemaster III'' within the [[Canadian Forces]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.airforce.forces.gc.ca/site/equip/c17/default_e.asp Aircraft – CC-177 Globemaster III]. Canada's Air Force.&lt;/ref&gt; The aircraft are assigned to [[Canadian Forces Air Command]]'s 429 Squadron based at CFB Trenton.

On 14 April 2010, a Canadian C-17 landed at [[Canadian Forces Station Alert]], the world's most northerly airport. It was Canada's first operational unpaved runway landing with a C-17.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.airforce.forces.gc.ca/v2/nr-sp/index-eng.asp?id=10443 Top of the world welcomes CC-177 Globemaster III]&lt;/ref&gt;
Canadian Globemasters have been deployed in support of numerous humanitarian and military missions worldwide, including [[Operation Hestia]] after the earthquake in Haiti, evacuations of foreign citizens from Libya, providing airlift as part of [[Operation MOBILE]] as well as ongoing support to the Canadian Forces in Afghanistan.

===NATO (Strategic Airlift Capability Program)===
[[File:C-17 1.jpg|thumb|A C-17 lands at [[Ramstein Air Base]], Germany, after dropping humanitarian food rations over Afghanistan.]]

A number of NATO countries signed a [[letter of intent]] to purchase C-17s on 19 July 2006 at the 2006 [[Farnborough Airshow]] to participate in the joint purchase and operation of C-17s within [[NATO]], a program called the [[NATO Strategic Airlift Capability]].&lt;ref name ='NATOairl'/&gt; A further letter of intent was announced on 12 September 2006 that included a few other countries, some of which have since withdrawn.

The present members are [[Bulgaria]], [[Estonia]], Hungary, [[Lithuania]], the Netherlands, Norway, Poland, [[Romania]], [[Slovenia]], the United States, as well as two [[Partnership for Peace]] countries Finland and Sweden.&lt;ref name ='NATOairl'&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.nato.int/issues/strategic-lift-air-sac/index.html |title = Strategic Airlift Capability: A key capability for the Alliance |publisher = NATO |accessdate = 01-04-2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The purchase is for two C-17s, and a third which is the US contribution to the pool, which is manned in the same fashion as the NATO [[E-3 Sentry|AWACS]] aircraft.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.e3a.nato.int/ |title = NATP Airborne Early Warning &amp; Control Force: E-3A Component |publisher = NATO |accessdate = 01-04-2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The AWACS aircraft are jointly manned by crew from NATO countries. The aircraft are based at Pápa Air Base in Hungary.

On 14 July 2009, Boeing delivered the first C-17 under NATO's Strategic Airlift Capability (SAC) program. The second and third C-17s were delivered in September and October 2009.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2009/07/15/329668/pictures-boeing-delivers-first-c-17-for-nato-led-heavy-airlift-wing.html &quot;Boeing delivers first C-17 for NATO-led Heavy Airlift Wing&quot;]. Flight International, 15 July 2009.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&amp;item=870 |title = 3rd Boeing C-17 Joins 12-Nation Strategic Airlift Capability Initiative |publisher = Boeing |date = 7 October 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Other===
[[File:Qatari C-17 at Incirlik Air Base, Turkey.JPG|thumb|[[Qatar Emiri Air Force]] C-17 at Incirlik Air Base, March 2011]]
The [[Qatar Emiri Air Force]] operates two Boeing C-17s. Boeing delivered Qatar's first C-17 on 11 August 2009 and the second on 10 September 2009.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&amp;item=832 |title = Boeing Delivers Qatar's 2nd C-17 Globemaster III |publisher = Boeing |date = 10 September 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Orders and deliveries==
===USAF===
[[File:C-17 Globemaster III.ogv|thumb|thumbtime=2|right|C-17 Globemaster III USAF video]]
In October 2007, 190 C-17s were on order to the USAF and Boeing had purchased parts for 30 new C-17s at its own expense in hopes that Congress would approve the funds requested.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.boeing.com/defense-space/military/c17/c17news.html |title = Boeing Company Funds Extension |publisher = Boeing |date = 9 July 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; 15 C-17s were earmarked in a FY2008 War Supplemental&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.armscontrolcenter.org/policy/securityspending/articles/analysis_c110_senate_may_supp/ |title = Analysis of Senate May 2008 Iraq-Afghanistan Supplemental War Funding for DOD |publisher = Center for Arms Control and Non-Proliferation |date = 21 May 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; that Congress passed and was signed into law in June 2008.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.defenselink.mil/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=50356 |title = Bush Signs $162 Billion Supplemental War Funding Bill |publisher = DoD |date = 30 June 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; These funds extended production from August 2009 to August 2010. On 6 February 2009, Boeing was awarded a contract for 15 additional C-17s for US$2.95 billion, thus pushing total C-17s on contract to the USAF to 205.&lt;ref name=&quot;Feb2009_contract&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2009/02/10/322315/usaf-signs-deals-for-15-more-c-17s-upgraded-c-5ms.html |title = Boeing in $3bn air force contract |first = Stephen |last = Trimble |publisher = ''Flight International'' |date = 10 February 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; On 6 April 2009, US Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]] announced that there would be no more C-17s ordered beyond the 205 planned.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |last = Cole |first = August |coauthors = Yochi J. Dreazen |title = Pentagon Pushes Weapon Cuts |publisher = ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' |date = 7 April 2009 |page = 1}}&lt;/ref&gt; This announcement may have been a bit early, because a month later in May a war funding bill was put forward that requested an additional US$2.2bn for up to eight more aircraft.&lt;ref name=&quot;LATimes1&quot;&gt;{{cite news |title= Boeing C-17 funds to be included in war spending bill |publisher= Los Angeles Times |date= 6 May 2009 |url= http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-briefs5-2009may05,0,716191.story |accessdate= 5 May 2009}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; And on 12 June 2009, the [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Air and Land Forces|House Armed Services Air and Land Forces Subcommittee]] added 17 C-17s to the authorized force level.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.govexec.com/dailyfed/0609/061209cdpm1.htm |title = House panel reverses cuts in aircraft programs |first = Otto |last = Kreisher |publisher = Congress Daily |date = 12 June 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In November 2009, 205 C-17s were on contract with the USAF. A contract for eight C-17s from the supplemental war funding bill has not yet been awarded. On 18 December 2009, the US Senate passed the FY 2010 DOD budget with funding for 10 C-17s and was signed into law by the President the following day. Total USAF C-17s contracted will be 223 once contracts are awarded, extending production until 2013.

In January 2010, the USAF announced that it would end Boeing's performance-based logistics contracts to maintain the aircraft, which was a key source for projected profit growth for the company.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2010/05/18/341939/why-is-usaf-bringing-maintenance-in-house.html Why is USAF bringing maintenance in-house?]&lt;/ref&gt;

===International===
In February 2009, the [[United Arab Emirates]] signed an agreement to purchase four C-17 airlifters.&lt;ref name=&quot;UAE_order&quot;&gt;Trimble, Stephen. [http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2009/02/25/323068/uae-strengthens-airlift-capacity-with-c-130j-c-17-deals.html &quot;UAE strengthens airlift capacity with C-130J, C-17 deals&quot;]. Flight International, 25 February 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; In January 2010, UAE signed a contract with Boeing for six C-17s (four C-17s in 2011, and two in 2012).&lt;ref name=UAE_order_6&gt;[http://www.indiastrategic.in/topstories461.htm &quot;Boeing, United Arab Emirates Announce Order for 6 C-17s&quot;]. indiastrategic.in, 6 January 2010.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=Boe_UAE_contract&gt;[http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&amp;item=1019 &quot;Boeing, United Arab Emirates Announce Order for 6 C-17s&quot;]. Boeing, 6 January 2010&lt;/ref&gt;

In June 2009, the [[Indian Air Force]] (IAF) selected the C-17 to fulfill its ''Very Heavy Lift Transport Aircraft'' requirement. The C-17 is to replace the [[Ilyushin Il-76]] as the IAF's largest heavy lift transport aircraft in service.&lt;ref name=DNA&gt;{{cite web |url= http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_russia-setting-us-rising-in-indian-air-force_1303530 |title= Russia setting, US rising in Indian air force |first= Josy |last= Joseph |publisher= DNA |date= 17 October 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.indiastrategic.in/topstories331.htm |title=IAF Chooses C 17 Globemaster III |last=Luthra |first=Gulshan |date=19 June 2009 |publisher= IndiaStrategic.in |accessdate= 15 June 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;C-17_orders_to_extend_line&quot;&gt;{{cite news |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/pressReleasesMolt/idUSTRE55F3TC20090616 |title=Boeing says C-17 orders to extend line |date= 16 June 2009 |publisher= Reuters |accessdate= 20 June 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; In January 2010, the US Government received a request from India for 10 C-17s through the US Government's [[Foreign Military Sales]] program,&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story.jsp?id=news/awx/2010/01/08/awx_01_08_2010_p0-195411.xml&amp;headline=India%20Requests%20Boeing%20C-17s&amp;channel=defense &quot;India Requests Boeing C-17s&quot;]. ''Aviation Week'', 8 January 2010.&lt;/ref&gt; and was approved by US Congress in June 2010.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.deccanchronicle.com/latest-news/us-congress-clears-c-17-sale-india-127 &quot;US Congress clears C-17 sale for India&quot;]. ''Deccan Chronicle'', 2 June 2010.&lt;/ref&gt; On 23 June 2010, the Indian Air Force successfully test-landed a USAF C-17 at the Gaggal Airport, India. This completed the IAF's C-17 trials.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.janes.com/news/defence/jdw/jdw100705_1_n.shtml &quot;IAF completes C-17 test-flight&quot;]. ''Jane's Information Group'', 5 July 2010.&lt;/ref&gt; An agreement to purchase 10 aircraft, with an option to purchase six more, was revealed during President Obama's visit to India in November 2010.&lt;ref name=mint&gt;http://www.livemint.com/2010/12/30224751/India-speeds-up-defence-procur.html?atype=tp&lt;/ref&gt; On 17 March 2011 the IAF finalized an order for 10 C-17s, but the order still needs to be approved by the Indian Cabinet Committee on Security.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url= http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/iaf-finalises-order-for-10-c-17-strategic-airlifters/articleshow/7729976.cms |work= The Times Of India |date= }}&lt;/ref&gt;

During the summer 2008 it was reported that [[South Korea]] had allocated funds for the purchase of three or four C-17-class airplanes for use in supporting expeditionary deployments.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url= http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_generic.jsp?channel=aerospacedaily&amp;id=news/C17090308.xml&amp;headline=C-17%20In%20Contention%20For%20South%20Korean%20Transport |title= C-17 In Contention For South Korean Transport |last= Perrett |first= Bradley |date= 3 September 2008 |publisher=Aviation Week |accessdate=24 December 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; In September 2010, Kuwait requested the purchase of one C-17, spare parts and support through the U.S.'s [[Foreign Military Sales]] (FMS) program.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.dsca.mil/PressReleases/36-b/2010/Kuwait_10-51.pdf &quot;Kuwait C-17 Globemaster III Aircraft and Related Support&quot;]. U.S. Defense Security Cooperation Agency, 24 September 2010.&lt;/ref&gt;

In March 2011, Australia's Minister for Defence [[Stephen Smith (Australian politician)|Stephen Smith]] announced that the nation had sent a Letter of Request to the United States about the possible purchase of a fifth C-17.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.minister.defence.gov.au/Smithtpl.cfm?CurrentId=11534 |title=C-17A Globemaster III Letter of Request |publisher=Australian Department of Defence |date=1 March 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; Australia ordered its fifth C-17 through the FMS program on 18 April 2011, due to an increased demand for humanitarian and disaster relief missions. Due to urgent requirements, the RAAF will receive an aircraft in August originally slated for the USAF.&lt;ref&gt;[http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&amp;item=1709 &quot;Boeing, Australia Announce Order for 5th C-17 Globemaster III&quot;] ''Boeing Press Release'' 18 April 2011&lt;/ref&gt;

===Production===
Due to a lack of sufficient orders, Boeing will deliver 13 C-17 Globemaster III airlifters in 2011. The company is transitioning to a lower production rate of 10 C-17s per year from a high of 16 per year in a bid to extend the production line through 2012 as it works to sign additional international orders. The C-17 production line was previously slated to be closed several times, but was extended due to new orders received.&lt;ref&gt;[http://boeing.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&amp;item=1588 &quot;Boeing C-17 Program Enters 2nd Phase of Production Rate and Work Force Reductions&quot;] ''Boeing Press Release'' 20 January 2011&lt;/ref&gt;

The C-17 work force will be reduced by approximately 1,100 through the end of 2012, mostly through the elimination of a second shift at the C-17 final assembly facility in Long Beach.

There have been 230 production C-17s delivered, including 210 to the USAF.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2011/04/19/355726/australia-to-get-fifth-c-17-in-august.html &quot;Australia to get fifth C-17 in August&quot;] By Craig Hoyle, Flightglobal. 19 April 2011&lt;/ref&gt; This does not include the &quot;T-1&quot; prototype test aircraft, which is still used by the USAF for testing and development.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.edwards.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123090905 &quot;Edwards T-1 reaches 1,000 flight milestone&quot;] by Senior Airman Stacy Sanchez, 95th Air Base Wing Public Affairs. 20 March 2008&lt;/ref&gt;

====Commercial interest====
In the mid-1990s, McDonnell Douglas began to market the C-17 to commercial civilian operators, under the name ''MD-17''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.boeing.com/news/releases/1997/news_release_970828n.html |title = MD-17 Receives FAA Certification |publisher = Boeing |date = 28 August 1997}}&lt;/ref&gt; Due to its high projected fuel, maintenance and depreciation cost for a low-cycle military design in commercial service, as well as a limited market dominated by the [[Antonov An-124|An-124]], very little interest was expressed. After McDonnell Douglas merged with Boeing, the commercial version was renamed ''BC-17''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url = http://www.boeing.com/news/releases/2000/news_release_000928a.html |title = Boeing proposes BC-17X |publisher = Boeing |date = 28 September 2000}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, the aircraft received no orders and Boeing stopped offering the [[Commercial Application of Military Airlift Aircraft|BC-17 for sale]].

