==Notable accidents and incidents==
{{anchor|Notable accidents and incidents}}&lt;!-- Please don't remove this- pages on other projects link to this section title --&gt;
[[File:C-17 at Bagram Air Base.jpg|thumb|C-17 on the runway at Bagram Air Base, Afghanistan on 31 January 2009 after landing with landing gear retracted.]]
&lt;!-- Add new items by date of notable incident
 --&gt;
* On 10 September 1998, a U.S. Air Force C-17 (AF Serial No.''96-0006'') suffered a landing gear failure as it landed in Vestmannaeyjar, Iceland, a {{convert|3800|ft|m|adj=on}} runway, to deliver [[Keiko (orca)|Keiko]] the whale. After receiving temporary repairs, it was flown to another city in Iceland for further repairs.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.mcchordairmuseum.org/REV%20B%20OUR%20HISTORY%20%20NAME%20C-17%2096-0006%20SP%20OF%20BERLIN.htm C-17A S/N 96-0006]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_6712/is_24_203/ai_n28736153/ &quot;C-17 Accident During Whale Lift Due To Design Flaw&quot;]&lt;/ref&gt; The total repair bill topped $1 million.

* On 10 December 2003, a U.S. Air Force C-17 (AF Serial No. ''98-0057'') was hit by a [[Surface-to-air missile|surface-to-air missile]] after take-off from Baghdad, Iraq. One engine was disabled and the aircraft returned for a safe landing.&lt;ref&gt;[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20031209-0 Information on 98-0057 incident], Aviation-Safety.net&lt;/ref&gt; The aircraft was repaired and returned to service.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.airliners.net/open.file/0614580/M/ C-17, tail 98-0057 image from 2004], airliners.net.&lt;/ref&gt;

* On 6 August 2005, a U.S. Air Force C-17 (AF Serial No. ''01-0196'') ran off the runway at Bagram Air Base in Afghanistan while attempting to land, destroying the airplane's nose and main landing gear. At the time, it was the most extensively damaged C-17 to date.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.defendamerica.mil/articles/aug2005/a080905wm5.html Bagram Runway Reopens After C-17 Incident  – DefendAmerica News Article]&lt;/ref&gt; A Boeing recovery team spent two months getting the aircraft ready to fly back to Boeing's Long Beach production facility.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.boeing.com/news/frontiers/archive/2006/february/i_ids1.html &quot;The Big Fix&quot;], Boeing Frontiers Online, February 2006.&lt;/ref&gt; The five-day flight back to the United States had to be performed by a [[test pilot]] because the temporary repairs caused numerous performance limitations.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.skypark.org/PilotsHonored.htm Skypark Pilots Honored], skypark.org&lt;/ref&gt; The repair was completed at Long Beach in October 2006 and the aircraft returned to service.

{{Wikinews|C-17 crashes near air force base in Alaska}}
* On 30 January 2009, a U.S. Air Force C-17 (AF Serial No. ''96-0002'' – &quot;Spirit of the Air Force&quot;) made a gear-up [[belly landing]] at [[Bagram Air Base]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123133880 &quot;Bagram Air Base runway recovery&quot;]. US Air Force, 4 February 2009.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.amc.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123148198 &quot;Bagram C-17 Accident Investigation Board complete&quot;]. U.S. Air Force, 7 May 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; By late April 2009, the C-17 was ferried from Bagram AB to Nova Scotia for an overnight stay after making several stops along the way. It later flew to Boeing's plant in Long Beach, California, for more permanent repairs. It is expected to return to service once the repairs are completed. The USAF Aircraft Accident Investigation Board concluded that the reason for the incident was the crew's failure to lower the [[undercarriage|landing gear]] as a consequence of omitting the pre-landing [[checklist]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Aircraft Accident Investigation Board Report |url=http://www.militarytimes.com/static/projects/pages/AIBreport.pdf| publisher=USAF Aircraft Accident Investigation Board| date=5 May 2009| accessdate=3 September 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

*On 28 July 2010, a U.S. Air Force C-17 (AF Serial No. ''00-0173'' – &quot;Spirit of the Aleutians&quot;) [[Alaska C-17 plane crash|crashed]] on [[Elmendorf Air Force Base]], Alaska during a training flight, killing all four aboard.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.q13fox.com/news/kcpq-072810-alaska-c17-crash,0,2100499.story &quot;BREAKING: C-17 Crashes At Air Force Base In Alaska&quot;]. q13fox.com, 28 July 2010.&lt;/ref&gt; It was practicing for the 2010 [[Arctic Thunder Air Show]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news |title= Military plane crashes on training mission in Alaska, killing 4 airmen |date= 29 July 2010|publisher=CNN |url= http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/07/29/alaska.plane.crash/index.html?hpt=T2 |accessdate= 29 July 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news |title= Four Dead in Alaska Air Force Base Crash |date= 29 July 2010|publisher= cbsnews.com |url= http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/07/29/national/main6723212.shtml?tag=stack |accessdate= 29 July 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; The plane crashed near a railroad, damaged tracks and disrupted rail operations.&lt;ref name=adn20100729&gt;{{Cite news |title=Arctic Thunder to continue after 4 died |date=  |publisher= adn.com |url= http://www.adn.com/2010/07/29/1387215/fatal-c-17-crash-also-damaged.html |accessdate= 30 July 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; A military investigative report determined that a [[stall (flight)|stall]] caused by pilot error led to the crash.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news |title= Pilot error cause of Alaska cargo plane crash, report concludes |date= December 11, 2010|publisher= CNN |url= http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/12/11/alaska.plane.crash/index.html?hpt=T2 |accessdate= 11 December 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; This is the first fatal operational C-17 accident and its first [[Aviation accidents and incidents|hull-loss incident]].&lt;ref name=adn20100729/&gt;

