==Canids and humans==
[[Image:BedaleHunt2005.jpg|thumb|Traditional English [[fox hunt]]]]
One canid, the domestic dog, a subspecies of the Gray Wolf, long ago entered into a partnership with humans and today remains one of the most widely kept domestic animals in the world and serves humanity in a great many important ways.

Among canids, only the gray wolf has been known to prey on humans.&lt;ref&gt;Kruuk, H. 2002. Hunter and Hunted: Relationships between Carnivores and People. Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press. ISBN 0521814103.&lt;/ref&gt; There are at least [[Coyote#Attacks_on_humans|two records]] of coyotes killing humans,&lt;ref name=&quot;AOH&quot;&gt;{{cite web | title = Coyote Attacks: An Increasing Suburban Problem | work = | publisher = | url = http://www.co.san-diego.ca.us/awm/docs/coyoteattacks.pdf | accessdate = 2007-08-19 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060224153601/http://www.co.san-diego.ca.us/awm/docs/coyoteattacks.pdf |archivedate = February 24, 2006}}&lt;/ref&gt; and two of golden jackals killing children.&lt;ref name=&quot;CWC&quot;&gt;{{cite web | title = Canis aureus | work = | publisher = Animal Diversity Web | url = http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Canis_aureus.html | accessdate = 2007-07-31}}&lt;/ref&gt; Some canid species have also been trapped and hunted for their fur and, especially the Gray Wolf and the Red Fox, for sport. Some canids are now endangered in the wild due to hunting, habitat loss, and the introduction of diseases from domestic dogs.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.iucnredlist.org/ ICUN Red List]&lt;/ref&gt;

