| style=&quot;font-style: italic;&quot; | '''Vancouver Island wolf'''&lt;/br&gt;[[Vancouver Island Wolf|Canis lupus crassodon]]
[[File:VIslandWolf.JPG|150 px]]
|  | Hall 1932
|  | A medium sized subspecies, it is generally greyish-white or white in fur color. It is a very social subspecies and can usually be found roaming in packs of five to thirty-five individuals.&lt;ref&gt;[http://books.google.com/books?id=LX5qi4qTs0UC&amp;pg=PA54&amp;lpg=PA54&amp;dq=%22vancouver+island+wolf%22&amp;source=web&amp;ots=zdNQ8bwOQt&amp;sig=XOGNPDTqmkKYDaX7Uf2MpW53_Lc#v=onepage&amp;q=%22vancouver%20island%20wolf%22&amp;f=false &quot;Preliminary Investigations of the Vancouver Island Wolf&quot;], ''Wolves of the world: perspectives of behavior, ecology, and conservation'' by Fred H. Harrington and Paul C. Paquet, William Andrew, 1982, Pg. 54&lt;/ref&gt;
|  | [[Vancouver Island]], [[British Columbia]]
|  | 
|- style=&quot;vertical-align: top;&quot;
| '''''Dingo'''''&lt;/br&gt;''[[Dingo|Canis lupus dingo]]'' 
[[File:Dingo-australian zoo.jpg|150 px]]
|  | Meyer 1793
|  | Generally 52–60&amp;nbsp;cm tall at the shoulders and measures 117 to 124&amp;nbsp;cm from nose to tail tip. The average weight is 13 to 20&amp;nbsp;kg.&lt;ref name=&quot;27kg&quot;&gt;{{cite web|author=Ben Allen|url=http://www.invasiveanimals.com/downloads/Final-proceedings-with-cover.pdf|title=Home Range, Activity Patterns, and Habitat use of Urban Dingoes|work=14th Australasian Vertebrate Pest Conference|publisher=Invasive Animals CRC|year=2008|accessdate=2009-04-29}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; Fur color is mostly sandy to reddish brown, but can include tan patterns and be occasionally black, light brown, or white&lt;ref name=&quot;impact&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last=Fleming|first=Peter|coauthor=Laurie Corbett, Robert Harden, Peter Thomson|title=Managing the Impacts of Dingoes and Other Wild Dogs|publisher=Bureau of Rural Sciences|location=Commonwealth of Australia|year=2001}}&lt;/ref&gt;
|  | [[Australia]], [[Thailand]], [[India]], [[Indonesia]] and [[New Guinea]]
|  | &lt;small&gt;''antarcticus'' (Kerr, 1792), ''australasiae'' (Desmarest, 1820), ''australiae'' (Gray, 1826), ''dingoides'' (Matschie, 1915), ''macdonnellensis'' (Matschie, 1915), ''novaehollandiae'' (Voigt, 1831), ''papuensis'' (Ramsay, 1879), ''tenggerana'' (Kohlbrugge, 1896), ''harappensis'' (Prashad, 1936), ''hallstromi'' (Troughton, 1957)&lt;/small&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{MSW3 Wozencraft | pages = | id =14000751 }}&lt;/ref&gt;
|- style=&quot;vertical-align: top;&quot;
| '''''Domestic dog'''''&lt;/br&gt;''[[Dog|Canis lupus familiaris]]'' [domestic dog]
[[File:YellowLabradorLooking new.jpg|150 px]]
|  | Linnaeus 1758
|  | Tends to have a 20% smaller skull and a 30% smaller brain,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author= Serpell, James| title=The Domestic Dog; its evolution, behaviour and interactions with people | year=1995 | isbn=0-521-42537-9 | publisher= Cambridge Univ. Press | location= Cambridge | page= 35 }}&lt;/ref&gt; as well as proportionately smaller teeth than other wolf subspecies&lt;ref name=&quot;DOGS&quot;&gt;{{cite book | author= Coppinger, Ray | title=Dogs: a Startling New Understanding of Canine Origin, Behavior and Evolution | year=2001 | isbn=0684855305 | publisher= Scribner | location= New York }}&lt;/ref&gt; The paws of a dog are half the size of those of a wolf, and their tails tend to curl upwards, another trait not found in wolves&lt;ref name=&quot;Lopez&quot;&gt;{{cite book | author = Lopez, Barry | title = Of wolves and men | year = 1978 | isbn = 0743249364 | publisher = Scribner Classics | location = New York | page = 320}}&lt;/ref&gt;
|  | Worldwide
|  | &lt;small&gt;''aegyptius'' (Linnaeus, 1758), ''alco'' (C. E. H. Smith, 1839), ''americanus'' (Gmelin, 1792), ''anglicus'' (Gmelin, 1792), ''antarcticus'' (Gmelin, 1792), ''aprinus'' (Gmelin, 1792), ''aquaticus'' (Linnaeus, 1758), ''aquatilis'' (Gmelin, 1792), ''avicularis'' (Gmelin, 1792), ''borealis'' (C. E. H. Smith, 1839), ''brevipilis'' (Gmelin, 1792)
