      <comment>Reverted edits by [[Special:Contributions/66.170.212.149|66.170.212.149]] ([[User talk:66.170.212.149|talk]]) to last revision by Jebus989 ([[WP:HG|HG]])</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">A '''cistron''' is a term used to describe the [[Locus (genetics)|locus]] responsible for generating a [[protein]].&lt;ref name=&quot;urlPerspectives glossary&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.nature.com/nrd/journal/v1/n11/glossary/nrd942_glossary.html |title=Perspectives glossary |format= |work= |accessdate=2008-11-10}}&lt;/ref&gt;
It can also be defined as the segment of [[DNA]] that contains all the information for production of single [[polypeptide]].&lt;ref&gt;Campbell. [[Biochemistry]] illustrated. Elsevier. 2005&lt;/ref&gt;

In [[eukaryotic]] [[genetics]], the concept is very similar to that of  [[open reading frame]], which is defined as a part of a gene which contains a sequence of bases which encodes for a complete protein. In eukaryotes, genes which function together in a single [[metabolic]] pathway may be located on different locations on a [[chromosome]], or on different chromosomes altogether. In contrast, in [[prokaryotes]], these [[gene]]s are often located near each other, and are subject to a common &quot;[[Messenger_RNA#Monocistronic_versus_polycistronic_mRNA|polycistronic]]&quot; regulatory mechanism. A cistron can also correspond to the [[transcription (genetics)|start and stop signals]] of the DNA.{{citation needed|date=June 2010}}

